questions.answer:
`const volatile` and `volatile const` are identical — both mean the variable is read-only from the program's perspective but may change externally.

**Use case:** Reading a hardware status register. Your code shouldn't write to it (`const`), but the hardware updates it (`volatile`), so the compiler must re-read it each time.

```c
// Read-only hardware status register
const volatile uint32_t *status = (const volatile uint32_t *)0x40001004;

// Each read hits the actual register, not a cached value
while (!(*status & READY_BIT)) { /* spin */ }
```

**Why both?** Without `volatile`, the compiler might read the register once and cache the value — your spin loop becomes infinite. Without `const`, nothing stops a developer from accidentally writing to a read-only register, potentially causing undefined hardware behavior.

