```c
bool is_power_of_2(uint32_t x) {
    return x != 0 && (x & (x - 1)) == 0;
}

uint32_t next_power_of_2(uint32_t x) {
    if (x == 0) return 1;
    x--;
    x |= x >> 1;
    x |= x >> 2;
    x |= x >> 4;
    x |= x >> 8;
    x |= x >> 16;
    return x + 1;
}
```

**How `is_power_of_2` works:** A power of 2 has exactly one bit set. `x-1` flips that bit and sets all lower bits. AND them together → 0.
- `8 = 0b1000`, `7 = 0b0111`, `8 & 7 = 0`

**How `next_power_of_2` works:** Subtract 1, then propagate the highest set bit right to fill all lower bits, then add 1.
- `5 → 4 → 0100 → 0111 → 1000 = 8`

**Firmware use:** Ring buffer sizes must be power of 2 for efficient `& (size-1)` masking instead of expensive modulo.

