questions.answer:
**Why NOT `*(volatile uint32_t *)addr`?**

While volatile prevents compiler optimization, it does NOT provide:
1. **Endianness handling:** Linux `readl`/`writel` perform little-endian byte swapping on big-endian architectures (e.g., some MIPS, PowerPC). Direct pointer access is endian-naive.
2. **Memory ordering barriers:** On ARM and other weakly-ordered architectures, stores/loads can be observed out of order by hardware. `readl`/`writel` include implicit barriers.
3. **Architecture portability:** On ARM, MMIO needs `dsb()` between independent register accesses in some contexts. `readl`/`writel` handle this.
4. **Debugging and tooling:** `readl`/`writel` can be intercepted by tracers, virtualization, and debug tools.

**What `readl`/`writel` provide:**
```c
/* Linux implementation (arm64 simplified): */
static inline u32 readl(const volatile void __iomem *addr) {
    u32 val;
    /* compiler barrier + ordering barrier: */
    __iomem_read_barrier();
    val = *(volatile u32 *)addr;
    return val;
}

static inline void writel(u32 val, volatile void __iomem *addr) {
    *(volatile u32 *)addr = val;
    __iomem_write_barrier();
}
```
On x86: the barriers are NOPs (strong memory model). On ARM: they expand to `dsb` or equivalent.

---

**Memory barriers in a display driver:**

| Function | Barrier type | Use when |
|----------|-------------|----------|
| `wmb()` | Write memory barrier | Before you want prior writes to be visible to hardware DMA / downstream reads |
| `rmb()` | Read memory barrier | After DMA completes, before reading the updated buffer |
| `mb()` | Full barrier (read+write) | General-purpose; use when unsure or in critical sync paths |
| `readl()`/`writel()` | Implicit I/O barrier | Correct for MMIO registers always |

**Display driver example:**
```c
/* Submit a new framebuffer to the display controller */
void display_flip(struct display_dev *dev, dma_addr_t fb_phys) {
    /* Write new framebuffer address to DMA register */
    writel(fb_phys, dev->base + FB_BASE_ADDR_REG);

    /* Barrier: ensure FB_BASE_ADDR_REG write completes before TRIGGER */
    wmb();

    /* Trigger the flip */
    writel(FLIP_TRIGGER_BIT, dev->base + CTRL_REG);
}

/* VBlank ISR */
irqreturn_t vblank_isr(int irq, void *dev_id) {
    /* Read status FIRST (acquires ordering) */
    u32 status = readl(dev->base + IRQ_STATUS_REG);
    rmb(); /* Ensure status is read before we act on it */

    if (status & FRAME_DONE_BIT) {
        writel(FRAME_DONE_BIT, dev->base + IRQ_CLR_REG); /* W1C */
        /* Schedule bottom-half processing */
    }
    return IRQ_HANDLED;
}
```

---

**When is `readl_relaxed()` safe?**

`readl_relaxed()` omits the synchronization barrier — it's just a volatile read. Use it ONLY when:
1. The register accesses are within the same device and the order relative to other MMIO doesn't matter
2. You're in a tight polling loop reading the same status register (barrier on each iteration wastes cycles)
3. The driver's own protocol guarantees ordering (e.g., always followed by a full `readl`)

**Never use `readl_relaxed` for:**
- Interrupt clear registers (HW requires the clear to be committed before re-enabling)
- DMA descriptor writes (must be visible to HW DMA engine before trigger)
- Cross-device ordering (use `mb()` explicitly)

**The `__iomem` annotation:** GCC + Sparse (Linux checker) warn if you dereference an `__iomem` pointer directly. It exists to enforce use of `readl`/`writel`.

RAII wraps hardware resource lifetime inside a C++ object's constructor/destructor, ensuring cleanup happens automatically even on early returns or exceptions.

**GPIO example:**
```cpp
class GpioPin {
public:
    explicit GpioPin(uint32_t pin, GpioMode mode)
        : pin_(pin) {
        GPIO_Init(pin_, mode);   // Acquire in constructor
    }
    ~GpioPin() {
        GPIO_Deinit(pin_);       // Release in destructor
    }
    void set(bool high) { GPIO_Write(pin_, high); }
    bool read() const { return GPIO_Read(pin_); }

    // Non-copyable — one owner
    GpioPin(const GpioPin&) = delete;
    GpioPin& operator=(const GpioPin&) = delete;
    // Movable
    GpioPin(GpioPin&& other) noexcept : pin_(other.pin_) { other.pin_ = INVALID_PIN; }
private:
    uint32_t pin_;
};

void do_work() {
    GpioPin cs{PA4, GPIO_OUTPUT};  // Configured on entry
    cs.set(false);                 // Assert chip select
    // ... do SPI transaction ...
    // cs automatically deasserted and deinitialized on scope exit
}
```

**DMA handle example:**
```cpp
class DmaChannel {
public:
    DmaChannel(DMA_TypeDef* dma, uint32_t channel)
        : dma_(dma), channel_(channel) {
        DMA_ClockEnable(dma_);
        DMA_ChannelInit(dma_, channel_);
    }
    ~DmaChannel() { DMA_ChannelDeinit(dma_, channel_); }
    // ... transfer methods ...
private:
    DMA_TypeDef* dma_;
    uint32_t channel_;
};
```

**Problems RAII solves:**
- Forgetting to deinit/release on all code paths
- Resource leaks on error returns
- Pin left in wrong state if init partially fails

**Trade-offs vs C manual management:**
| RAII | Manual C |
|------|----------|
| Automatic cleanup | Explicit, error-prone |
| Zero-cost if inlined | No overhead |
| Harder to share/pass around | Trivial to pass pointers |
| Requires C++ build toolchain | C everywhere |
| Destructor order can be subtle in globals | Explicit teardown order |

**Key concern for embedded:** Destructor must be marked `noexcept` (default). Avoid virtual destructors unless needed — they add vtable overhead on tiny MCUs.

```cpp
#include <cstdint>

// CRTP base — Derived must implement read_impl()
template <typename Derived>
class Sensor {
public:
    // Non-virtual dispatch — resolved at compile time
    int32_t read() {
        return static_cast<Derived*>(this)->read_impl();
    }
    // Common behavior built on top of read()
    bool is_saturated() { return read() >= Derived::MAX_VALUE; }
};

// Concrete sensor A: ADC temperature sensor
class TempSensor : public Sensor<TempSensor> {
public:
    static constexpr int32_t MAX_VALUE = 125;  // °C max
    int32_t read_impl() {
        // Read 12-bit ADC, convert to °C
        uint16_t raw = ADC1->DR & 0x0FFF;
        return (raw * 330) / 4096 - 40;  // simplified
    }
};

// Concrete sensor B: I2C pressure sensor
class PressureSensor : public Sensor<PressureSensor> {
public:
    static constexpr int32_t MAX_VALUE = 1200;  // hPa max
    int32_t read_impl() {
        uint8_t buf[3];
        i2c_read(BARO_ADDR, REG_DATA, buf, 3);
        return (buf[0] << 12) | (buf[1] << 4) | (buf[2] >> 4);
    }
};

// Generic function: works with ANY CRTP sensor, fully inlined
template <typename SensorType>
void log_sensor(SensorType& sensor, const char* name) {
    int32_t val = sensor.read();  // Compile-time dispatch — no vtable lookup
    printf("%s: %ld\n", name, val);
    if (sensor.is_saturated()) {
        printf("%s SATURATED!\n", name);
    }
}

int main() {
    TempSensor    temp;
    PressureSensor baro;
    log_sensor(temp, "Temperature");  // Instantiated for TempSensor
    log_sensor(baro, "Pressure");     // Instantiated for PressureSensor
}
```

**Why zero-cost:**
- `static_cast<Derived*>(this)->read_impl()` is resolved at compile time
- The compiler can inline `read_impl()` into `read()` — no function call overhead at all
- No vtptr in each object, no vtable, no indirect branch
- Generated assembly is identical to calling `read_impl()` directly

**Trade-offs vs virtual:**
| CRTP | Virtual |
|------|---------|
| Zero runtime overhead | Small overhead per call |
| Fully inlinable | Never inlined across vtable |
| Compile-time only — can't mix sensor types in one array | `Sensor* sensors[4]` — runtime polymorphism |
| More complex template syntax | Simple OO syntax |
| Code bloat: separate instantiation per type | Single vtable dispatch |

**Limitation:** You cannot store `Sensor<TempSensor>*` and `Sensor<PressureSensor>*` in the same array — CRTP does not support runtime polymorphism. For that you still need virtual or a type-erased wrapper.

